A va&s;t encrea&s;e in&s;tead of diminution. The expe|rience then of the two la&s;t years ought naturally to have given the idea of an heavier e&s;tabli&s;h|ment; but this writer is able to dimini&s;h by en|crea&s;ing, and to draw the effects of &s;ubtraction from the operations of addition. By means of
<PB N="71" REF="74">
the&s;e new powers, he may certainly do whatever he plea&s;es. He is indeed moderate enough in the u&s;e of them, and conde&s;cends to &s;ettle his e&s;tabli&s;h|ments at &pound;. 3.468.161 a year.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, he has not yet done with it; he has further ideas of &s;aving, and new re&s;ources of re|venue. The&s;e additional &s;avings are principally two: 1&s;t, <HI>It is to be hoped,</HI> &s;ays he,<NOTE N="p" PLACE="foot">P. 34.</NOTE> that the &s;um of &pound;. 250.000 (which in the e&s;timate he allows for the deficiency of land and malt) will be le&s;s by &pound;. 37.924.<NOTE N="q" PLACE="foot"><P>In making up this account, he falls into a &s;urprizing error of arithmetic.
<Q REND="inline margQuotes"><NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">P. 3.</NOTE>"The deficiency of the land-tax in the year 1754 and 1755, when it was at 2s. amounted to no more, on a medium, than &pound;. 40.372; to which, if we add <HI>half the &s;um,</HI> it will give us &pound;. 79.058 as the peace defici|ency at 3s."</Q>
